# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voxel-global-illumination
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] In ray tracing, rays are often modeled as geometric ray with no thickness to perform efficient geometric queries such as a ray-triangle intersection.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] From a physics of light transport point of view, however, this is an inaccurate model provided the pixel on the sensor plane has non-zero area.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] In the simplified pinhole camera optics model, the energy reaching the pixel comes from the integral of radiance from the solid angle by which the sensor pixel sees the scene through the pinhole at the focal plane.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] This yields the key notion of **pixel footprint** on surfaces or in the texture space, which is the back projection of the pixel on to the scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Note that this approach can also represent a lens-based camera and thus depth of field effects, using a cone whose cross-section decreases from the lens size to zero at the focal plane, and then increases.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Real optical system do not focus on exact points because of diffraction and imperfections.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] This can be modeled with a point spread function (PSF) weighted within a solid angle larger than the pixel.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] The physically based image formation model can be approximated by the convolution with the point spread function assuming the function is shift-invariant and linear.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] In practice, techniques such as multisample anti-aliasing estimate this cone-based model by oversampling the signal and then performing a convolution (the reconstruction filter).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] The backprojected cone footprint onto the scene can also be used to directly pre-filter the geometry and textures of the scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Note that contrary to intuition, the reconstruction filter should not be the pixel footprint (as the pinhole camera model would suggest), since a box filter has poor spectral properties.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Conversely, the ideal sinc function is not practical, having infinite support with possibly negative values which often creates ringing artifacts due to the Gibbs phenomenon.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] A Gaussian or a Lanczos filter are considered good compromises.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Cone and Beam early papers rely on different simplifications: the first considers a circular section and treats the intersection with various possible shapes.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] The second treats an accurate pyramidal beam through the pixel and along a complex path, but it only works for polyhedrical shapes.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Cone tracing solves certain problems related to sampling and aliasing, which can plague conventional ray tracing.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] However, cone tracing creates a host of problems of its own.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] For example, just intersecting a cone with scene geometry leads to an enormous variety of possible results.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] For this reason, cone tracing has remained mostly unpopular.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] In recent years, increases in computer speed have made Monte Carlo algorithms like distributed ray tracing - i.e. stochastic explicit integration of the pixel - much more used than cone tracing because the results are exact provided enough samples are used.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] But the convergence is so slow that even in the context of off-line rendering a huge amount of time can be required to avoid noise.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Differential cone-tracing, considering a differential angular neighborhood around a ray, avoids the complexity of exact geometry intersection but requires a LOD representation of the geometry and appearance of the objects.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] MIPmapping is an approximation of it limited to the integration of the surface texture within a cone footprint.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Differential ray-tracing extends it to textured surfaces viewed through complex paths of cones reflected or refracted by curved surfaces.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Raymarching methods over signed distance fields (SDFs) naturally allow easy use of cone-like tracing, at zero additional cost to the tracing, and both speeds up tracing and improves quality.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] Voxel cone tracing is a real-time algorithm that uses a hierarchical voxel representation of scene geometry, such as a sparse voxel octree, to support fast cone tracing for indirect illumination.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/cone-tracing] This approach allows for the approximation of effects like glossy reflections and ambient occlusion at interactive framerates without the need for precomputation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Areas that lie outside of the ceiling lamp's direct light lack definition.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] For example, the lamp's housing appears completely uniform.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Without the ambient light added into the render, it would appear uniformly black.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Light is reflected by surfaces, and colored light transfers from one surface to another.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Notice how color from the red wall and green wall (not visible) reflects onto other surfaces in the scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] projected onto the red wall from light passing through the glass sphere.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Theoretically, reflections, refractions, transparency, and shadows are all examples of global illumination, because when simulating them, one object affects the rendering of another (as opposed to an object being affected only by a direct source of light).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] In practice, however, only the simulation of diffuse inter-reflection or caustics is called global illumination, especially in real-time settings.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Global illumination is a key aspect to the realism of a 3D scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Naive 3D lighting will only take into account direct light, meaning any light which radiates off a light source and bounces directly into the virtual camera.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Shadows will appear completely dark, due to light not interacting with any other surface before it reaches the camera.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] As this is not what occurs in real life, we perceive the resulting image as incomplete.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Applying full global illumination allows for the missing effects that makes an image feel more natural.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] However, global illumination is computationally more expensive and consequently much slower to generate.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] The algorithms used to calculate the distribution of light energy between surfaces of a scene are closely related to heat transfer simulations performed using finite-element methods in engineering design.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Achieving accurate computation of global illumination in real-time remains difficult.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] On one end, the diffuse inter-reflection component of global illumination is sometimes approximated by an "ambient" term in the lighting equation, which is also called "ambient lighting" or "ambient color" in 3D software.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Though this method is one of the cheapest ways to simulate indirect lighting, when used alone it does not provide an adequately realistic effect.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Ambient lighting is known to "flatten" shadows in 3D scenes, making the overall visual effect more bland.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Beyond ambient lighting, techniques which trace the path of light accurately have historically been either too slow for consumer hardware or limited to static and precomputed environments.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] This proves problematic, as most applications allow for input from a user that can affect their surroundings, and the precalculation steps may introduce constraints upon the artists.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Consequently, research has been dedicated to finding a balance between adequate performance, accurate visual results, and interactivity.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Starting with Nvidia's RTX 20 series, consumer graphics hardware has been extended to allow for ray tracing computations to be performed in real time through hardware acceleration.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] This has allowed for further improvements, as applications can now harness the power of this acceleration to provide not only precise lighting results, but the ability to affect said lighting dynamically.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Some content that has taken advantage of this capability includes Cyberpunk 2077, Indiana Jones and the Great Circle, and Alan Wake 2, among others.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] For an overview of the current state of real-time global illumination, see or.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Algorithms which attempt to simulate global illumination are numerical approximations of the rendering equation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/global-illumination] Well-known algorithms for computing global illumination include path tracing, photon mapping and radiosity.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The amount of light transported is measured by **flux density**, or luminous flux per unit area on the point of the surface at which it is measured.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport describes the propagation of visible electromagnetic energy in macroscopic environments.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The mathematical theory underpinning light transport can be described by the Hamiltonian approach.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] where H is the Hamiltonian and l is the light energy density.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] In such a form, the light transport equation is identical to the phase space Liouville equation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Radiometry is the science of measuring electromagnetic radiation, including visible light.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It forms the foundation of light transport theory, which models how light interacts with surfaces, volumes, and media.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Given a surface S, a hemisphere H can be projected onto S to calculate the amount of incoming and outgoing light.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] If a point P is selected at random on the surface S, the amount of incoming and outgoing light can be calculated by its projection onto the hemisphere.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The **hemicube model** works similarly to the hemisphere model, except that a hemicube is projected instead of a hemisphere.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The similarity is only conceptual; the actual calculation, done through numerical integration, has a different form factor.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport theory incorporates both **wave-based** and **particle-based** descriptions of light.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] While wave-based models rely on the principles of Maxwell's equations, particle models use ray optics and Monte Carlo methods to simulate light paths.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The BRDF models how light is reflected on an opaque surface.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It is defined as the ratio of reflected radiance in a given direction to the incident irradiance.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] BRDFs are crucial in light transport theory for simulating realistic material behavior.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport within volumes (e.g., fog, smoke, or translucent objects) is modeled using the radiative transfer equation (RTE).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Participating media are integral to achieving photorealism in scenes involving volumetric light effects.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating a method, such as light transport, to get physically accurate photorealistic images, or by applying some kind of style as non-photorealistic rendering (NPR).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The two basic operations in light transport are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Global illumination simulates all light interactions in a scene, including indirect lighting.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It employs light transport theory to compute effects such as color bleeding and soft shadows.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Unlike photorealistic rendering, non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses light transport models to stylize images, often prioritizing artistic intent over physical accuracy.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] An **octree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly eight children.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Octrees are most often used to partition a three-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into eight octants.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Octrees are the three-dimensional analog of quadtrees.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The word is derived from *oct* (Greek root meaning "eight") + *tree*.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Octrees are often used in 3D graphics and 3D game engines.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Each node in an octree subdivides the space it represents into eight octants.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] In a point region (PR) octree (analogous to a point quadtree), the node stores an explicit three-dimensional point, which is the "center" of the subdivision for that node; the point defines one of the corners for each of the eight children.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] In a matrix-based (MX) octree (analogous to a region quadtree), the subdivision point is implicitly the center of the space the node represents.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The root node of a PR octree can represent infinite space; the root node of an MX octree must represent a finite bounded space so that the implicit centers are well-defined.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Note that octrees are not the same as *k*-d trees: *k*-d trees split along a dimension and octrees split around a point.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Also *k*-d trees are always binary, which is not the case for octrees.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] By using a depth-first search the nodes are to be traversed and only required surfaces are to be viewed.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] A spatial subdivision much like an octree was used in 1934, in the Whitney covering lemma in mathematics.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The octree color quantization algorithm, invented by Gervautz and Purgathofer in 1988, encodes image color data as an octree up to nine levels deep.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Octrees are used because $2^{3}=8$ and there are three color components in the RGB system.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The node index to branch out from at the top level is determined by a formula that uses the most significant bits of the red, green, and blue color components, e.g.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The next lower level uses the next bit significance, and so on.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Less significant bits are sometimes ignored to reduce the tree size.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The algorithm is highly memory efficient because the tree's size can be limited.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The bottom level of the octree consists of leaf nodes that accrue color data not represented in the tree; these nodes initially contain single bits.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] If much more than the desired number of palette colors are entered into the octree, its size can be continually reduced by seeking out a bottom-level node and averaging its bit data up into a leaf node, pruning part of the tree.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Once sampling is complete, exploring all routes in the tree down to the leaf nodes, taking note of the bits along the way, will yield approximately the required number of colors.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The example recursive algorithm outline below (MATLAB syntax) decomposes an array of 3-dimensional points into octree style bins.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The implementation begins with a single bin surrounding all given points, which then recursively subdivides into its 8 octree regions.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Recursion is stopped when a given exit condition is met.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Taking the full list of colors of a 24-bit RGB image as point input to the Octree point decomposition implementation outlined above, the following example show the results of octree color quantization.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] The first image is the original (532818 distinct colors), while the second is the quantized image (184 distinct colors) using octree decomposition, with each pixel assigned the color at the center of the octree bin in which it falls.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/octree] Alternatively, final colors could be chosen at the centroid of all colors in each octree bin, however this added computation has very little effect on the visual result.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In 3D computer graphics, **radiosity** is an application of the finite element method to solving the rendering equation for scenes with surfaces that reflect light diffusely.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity is a global illumination algorithm in the sense that the illumination arriving on a surface comes not just directly from the light sources, but also from other surfaces reflecting light.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity is viewpoint independent, which increases the calculations involved, but makes them useful for all viewpoints.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity methods were first developed in about 1950 in the engineering field of heat transfer.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] They were later refined specifically for the problem of rendering computer graphics in 1984–1985 by researchers at Cornell University and Hiroshima University.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Notable commercial radiosity engines are Enlighten by Geomerics (used for games including Battlefield 3 and Need for Speed: The Run); 3ds Max; form•Z; LightWave 3D and the Electric Image Animation System.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The inclusion of radiosity calculations in the rendering process often lends an added element of realism to the finished scene, because of the way it mimics real-world phenomena.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The image on the left was rendered with a typical **direct illumination renderer**.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The image on the right was rendered using a **radiosity algorithm**.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] There is only **one source of light**: an image of the sky placed outside the window.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Soft shadows are visible on the floor, and subtle lighting effects are noticeable around the room.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Furthermore, the red color from the carpet has bled onto the grey walls, giving them a slightly warm appearance.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] None of these effects were specifically chosen or designed by the artist.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The surfaces of the scene to be rendered are each divided up into one or more smaller surfaces (patches).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] A view factor (also known as *form factor*) is computed for each pair of patches; it is a coefficient describing how well the patches can see each other.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Patches that are far away from each other, or oriented at oblique angles relative to one another, will have smaller view factors.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] If other patches are in the way, the view factor will be reduced or zero, depending on whether the occlusion is partial or total.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The view factors are used as coefficients in a linear system of rendering equations.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Solving this system yields the radiosity, or brightness, of each patch, taking into account diffuse interreflections and soft shadows.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Progressive radiosity solves the system iteratively with intermediate radiosity values for the patch, corresponding to bounce levels.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] That is, after each iteration, we know how the scene looks after one light bounce, after two passes, two bounces, and so forth.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is useful for getting an interactive preview of the scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Also, the user can stop the iterations once the image looks good enough, rather than wait for the computation to numerically converge.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Another common method for solving the radiosity equation is "shooting radiosity," which iteratively solves the radiosity equation by "shooting" light from the patch with the most energy at each step.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After the first pass, only those patches which are in direct line of sight of a light-emitting patch will be illuminated.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After the second pass, more patches will become illuminated as the light begins to bounce around the scene.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The scene continues to grow brighter and eventually reaches a steady state.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The basic radiosity method has its basis in the theory of thermal radiation, since radiosity relies on computing the amount of light energy transferred among surfaces.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In order to simplify computations, the method assumes that all scattering is perfectly diffuse.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Surfaces are typically discretized into quadrilateral or triangular elements over which a piecewise polynomial function is defined.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After this breakdown, the amount of light energy transfer can be computed by using the known reflectivity of the reflecting patch, combined with the view factor of the two patches.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This dimensionless quantity is computed from the geometric orientation of two patches, and can be thought of as the fraction of the total possible emitting area of the first patch which is covered by the second.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] where *Fij* is the geometrical view factor for the radiation leaving *j* and hitting patch *i*.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This equation can then be applied to each patch.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The equation is monochromatic, so color radiosity rendering requires calculation for each of the required colors.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This gives the full "infinite bounce" solution for B directly.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However the number of calculations to compute the matrix solution scales according to *n*3, where *n* is the number of patches.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This becomes prohibitive for realistically large values of *n*.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Instead, the equation can more readily be solved iteratively, by repeatedly applying the single-bounce update formula above.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Formally, this is a solution of the matrix equation by Jacobi iteration.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Because the reflectivities ρi are less than 1, this scheme converges quickly, typically requiring only a handful of iterations to produce a reasonable solution.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Other standard iterative methods for matrix equation solutions can also be used, for example the Gauss–Seidel method, where updated values for each patch are used in the calculation as soon as they are computed, rather than all being updated synchronously at the end of each sweep.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The solution can also be tweaked to iterate over each of the sending elements in turn in its main outermost loop for each update, rather than each of the receiving patches.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is known as the *shooting* variant of the algorithm, as opposed to the *gathering* variant.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is sometimes known as the "power" formulation, since it is now the total transmitted power of each element that is being updated, rather than its radiosity.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The view factor *F*ij itself can be calculated in a number of ways.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Early methods used a *hemicube* (an imaginary cube centered upon the first surface to which the second surface was projected, devised by Michael F.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The surface of the hemicube was divided into pixel-like squares, for each of which a view factor can be readily calculated analytically.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The full form factor could then be approximated by adding up the contribution from each of the pixel-like squares.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The projection onto the hemicube, which could be adapted from standard methods for determining the visibility of polygons, also solved the problem of intervening patches partially obscuring those behind.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However all this was quite computationally expensive, because ideally form factors must be derived for every possible pair of patches, leading to a quadratic increase in computation as the number of patches increased.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This can be reduced somewhat by using a binary space partitioning tree to reduce the amount of time spent determining which patches are completely hidden from others in complex scenes; but even so, the time spent to determine the form factor still typically scales as *n* log *n*.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] New methods include adaptive integration.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The form factors *F*ij themselves are not in fact explicitly needed in either of the update equations; neither to estimate the total intensity Σj *F*ij *B*j gathered from the whole view, nor to estimate how the power *A*j *B*j being radiated is distributed.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Instead, these updates can be estimated by sampling methods, without ever having to calculate form factors explicitly.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Since the mid 1990s such sampling approaches have been the methods most predominantly used for practical radiosity calculations.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The gathered intensity can be estimated by generating a set of samples in the unit circle, lifting these onto the hemisphere, and then seeing what was the radiosity of the element that a ray incoming in that direction would have originated on.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The estimate for the total gathered intensity is then just the average of the radiosities discovered by each ray.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Similarly, in the power formulation, power can be distributed by generating a set of rays from the radiating element in the same way, and spreading the power to be distributed equally between each element a ray hits.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is essentially the same distribution that a path-tracing program would sample in tracing back one diffuse reflection step; or that a bidirectional ray-tracing program would sample to achieve one forward diffuse reflection step when light source mapping forwards.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Static, pre-computed radiosity may be displayed in real time via lightmaps using standard rasterization techniques.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Typical radiosity methods only account for light paths of the form LD*E, i.e. paths which start at a light source and make multiple diffuse bounces before reaching the eye.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Although there are several approaches to integrating other illumination effects such as specular and glossy reflections, radiosity-based methods are generally not used to solve the complete rendering equation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Basic radiosity also has trouble resolving sudden changes in visibility (e.g. hard-edged shadows) because coarse, regular discretization into piecewise constant elements corresponds to a low-pass box filter of the spatial domain.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Discontinuity meshing [1] uses knowledge of visibility events to generate a more intelligent discretization.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity was perhaps the first rendering algorithm in widespread use which accounted for diffuse indirect lighting.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However, the three are distinct concepts.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The radiosity method, in the context of computer graphics, derives from (and is fundamentally the same as) the radiosity method in heat transfer.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In this context, radiosity is the total radiative flux (both reflected and re-radiated) leaving a surface; this is also sometimes known as radiant exitance.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Calculation of radiosity, rather than surface temperatures, is a key aspect of the radiosity method that permits linear matrix methods to be applied to the problem.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] A **sparse voxel octree** (**SVO**) is a hierarchical octree data structure in which voxels recursively subdivide space into octants, storing only occupied or surface-intersecting regions, making it compact for raycasting and sometimes ray tracing in 3D computer graphics rendering.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] The technique generally relies on generating and processing the hull of points (sparse voxels) which are visible, or may be visible, given the resolution and size of the screen.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] There are two main advantages to the technique.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] The first is that only pixels that will be displayed are computed, with the screen resolution limiting the level of detail required; this limits computational cost during rendering.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] The second is that interior voxels (those fully enclosed by other voxels) need not be included in the 3D data set; this limits the amount of 3D voxel data (and thus storage space) required for realistic, high-resolution digital models and/or environments.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] The basic advantage of octrees is that, as a hierarchical data structure, they need not be explored to their full depth.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] This means that a system can extract a small subset of voxels as they are needed.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] In addition, octrees permit smoothing of the underlying data, to help with antialiasing.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] It is, however, a generally less well developed technique than standard polygon-based rasterisation schemes.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] As scenes grow in geometric complexity, SVOs have been proposed to facilitate a transition from traditional triangle-based pipelines to voxel-based rendering.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] Each non-leaf node in an SVO subdivides its voxel into eight child slots of equal size.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] Implementations such as efficient sparse voxel octrees encode which child slots exist and which are leaves with bitmasks, together with a child pointer for non-leaf descendants, so rays can traverse only relevant children instead of empty space.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/sparse-voxel-octree] SVOs support seamless level of detail (LOD) by storing pre-filtered geometry and appearance data at each level, allowing ray casting to terminate early when voxel size matches screen resolution.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] In computing, a **voxel** is a representation of a value on a three-dimensional regular grid, akin to the two-dimensional pixel.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Voxels are frequently used in the visualization and analysis of medical and scientific data (e.g. geographic information systems (G.I.S.)).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Voxels also have technical and artistic applications in video games, largely originating with surface rendering in *Outcast* (1999).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] *Minecraft* (2011) makes use of an entirely voxelated world to allow for a fully destructible and constructable environment.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] **Voxel art**, of the sort used in *Minecraft* and elsewhere, is a style and format of 3D art analogous to pixel art.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] As with pixels in a 2D bitmap, voxels themselves do not typically have their position (i.e. coordinates) explicitly encoded with their values.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Instead, rendering systems infer the position of a voxel based upon its position relative to other voxels (i.e., its position in the data structure that makes up a single volumetric image).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Some volumetric displays use voxels to describe their resolution.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] For example, a cubic volumetric display might be able to show 512×512×512 (or about 134 million) voxels.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] In contrast to pixels and voxels, polygons are often explicitly represented by the coordinates of their vertices (as points).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A direct consequence of this difference is that polygons can efficiently represent simple 3D structures with much empty or homogeneously filled space, while voxels excel at representing regularly sampled spaces that are non-homogeneously filled.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] This definition has the following advantage.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] If fixed voxel form is used within the whole model it is much easier to operate with voxel *nodal points* (i.e. three coordinates of this point).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Yet, there is the simple form of record: indexes of the elements in the model set (i.e. integer coordinates).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Model set elements in this case are *state parameters,* indicating voxel belonging to the modeled object or its separate parts, including their surfaces.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] The word *voxel* originated by analogy to "pixel", with *vo* representing "volume" (instead of pixel's "picture") and *el* representing "element"; a similar formation with *el* for "element" is the word "texel".
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] The term *hypervoxel* is a generalization of voxel for higher-dimensional spaces.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A volume described as voxels can be visualized either by direct volume rendering or by the extraction of polygon iso-surfaces that follow the contours of given threshold values.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] The marching cubes algorithm(s) and Inertial frame of reference(s) are often used for iso-surface extraction, however other methods exist as well.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Both ray tracing and ray casting, as well as rasterisation, can be applied to voxel data to obtain 2D raster graphics to depict on a monitor.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Another technique for voxels involves raster graphics where one simply raytraces every pixel of the display into the scene, tracking an error term to determine when to step.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A typical implementation will raytrace each pixel of the display starting at the bottom of the screen using what is known as a y-buffer.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] When a voxel is reached that has a higher y value on the display it is added to the y-buffer overriding the previous value and connected with the previous y-value on the screen interpolating the color values.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] There is a major downside to voxel rasterization when transformation is applied which causes severe aliasing.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] The advantage was the ability to rasterise using cheap integer calculations on a CPU without hardware acceleration.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] John Carmack also experimented with voxels for the *Quake III Arena* engine.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] One such problem cited by Carmack was the lack of graphics cards designed specifically for such rendering requiring them to be software rendered.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A voxel represents a single sample, or data point, on a regularly spaced, three-dimensional grid.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] This data point can consist of a single datum, such as an opacity, or multiple data, such as a color in addition to opacity.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A voxel represents only a single point on this grid, not a volume; the space between each voxel is not represented in a voxel-based data set.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Depending on the type of data and the intended use for the data set, this missing information may be reconstructed and/or approximated, e.g. via interpolation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] The value of a voxel may represent various properties.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] In C.T. scans, the values are Hounsfield units, giving the opacity of material to X-rays.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Different types of value are acquired from M.R.I. or ultrasound.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Voxels can contain multiple scalar values, essentially vector (tensor) data; in the case of ultrasound scans with B-mode and Doppler data, density, and volumetric flow rate are captured as separate channels of data relating to the same voxel positions.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] While voxels provide the benefit of precision and depth of reality, they are typically large data sets and are unwieldy to manage given the bandwidth of common computers.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] However, through efficient compression and manipulation of large data files, interactive visualization can be enabled on consumer market computers.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Other values may be useful for immediate 3D rendering, such as a surface normal vector and color.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Technologies to extend voxels into four and five dimensions of data are under investigation.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Uses of voxels include volumetric imaging in medicine and representation of terrain in games and simulations.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Voxel terrain is used instead of a heightmap because of its ability to represent overhangs, caves, arches, and other 3D terrain features.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] These concave features cannot be represented in a heightmap due to only the top 'layer' of data being represented, leaving everything below it filled (the volume that would otherwise be the inside of the caves, or the underside of arches or overhangs).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] While scientific volume visualization does not require modifying the actual voxel data, voxel editors can be used to create art (especially 3D pixel art) and models for voxel-based games.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Some editors are focused on a single approach to voxel editing while others mix various approaches.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] There are a few voxel editors available that are not tied to specific games or engines.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] They can be used as alternatives or complements to traditional 3D vector modeling.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] A generalization of a voxel is the *toxel*, or temporal voxel.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] This is used in the case of a 4D data set, such as an image sequence that represents 3D space together with another spatial dimension or a time dimension.
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] In this way, an image could contain 100×100×100×100 voxels, which could be seen as a series of 100 frames of a 100×100×100 volume image (the equivalent for a 3D image would be showing a 2D cross-section of the image in each frame).
[src:voxel-global-illumination/voxel] Although storage and manipulation of such data requires large amounts of memory, it allows the representation and analysis of spacetime systems.
